        {
            "id": 3896,
            "type": "Article",
            "title": "Myths and facts regarding vaccines",
            "created_at": "\u003Ctime datetime=\"2025-05-22T13:06:38+02:00\" class=\"datetime\"\u003EThu, 05/22/2025 - 13:06\u003C/time\u003E\n",
            "updated_at": "\u003Ctime datetime=\"2026-05-19T04:27:59+02:00\" class=\"datetime\"\u003ETue, 05/19/2026 - 04:27\u003C/time\u003E\n",
            "summary": "The broad usage of vaccines around the world has been accompanied by lots of concerns regarding their safety and possible influences and long term side effects. In the following paragraph we will summarize the facts regarding these concerns.",
            "body": "\u003Cp\u003EThe broad usage of vaccines around the word has been accompanied by lots of concerns regarding their safety and possible influences and long term side effects. In the following paragraph we will summarize the facts regarding these concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is always ok and even justified to be concern and look for information regarding medical issues in general, and specifically regarding vaccines. However, we strongly suggest following information from reliable sources like central health organizations such as the WHO, the European Medical Agency, The American academy of pediatrics etc. The electronic media is flooded with information that a big part of it is without scientific base and sometime even intentionally false and \"fake\".\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is very important to separate between \"temporal association\"; When two events happen by co-incidence one after the other to \"'cause and effect\" association. In many cases when two events happen one after the other, there no reason to believe that the first event caused the second one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor example, if an earthquake happened 1 day after a loss of the national football team no one would believe that the loss caused the earthquake.  This is just a co-incidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is the case with several bad things that may happen following vaccination: we should remember that many of the genetic and developmental illnesses appear during the first 2 years of life. This is also the time when most of the vaccines are given. It is very tempting to believe that the vaccine caused the illness. However we need to find out if this was a co-incidence or really a cause and effect issue. Therefore many huge epidemiological studies have been done with several methods of investigations and in different countries with different researchers. The overwhelming mass of evidences provides a very reassuring message that vaccines are very safe and do not cause serious diseases.\u003C/p\u003E",
            "field_type_of_article": 0,
            "category": 386,
            "subcategory": 13856,
            "child_age": [626, 631, 636, 641, 646, 651, 656, 661, 666, 671, 676, 681],
            "child_gender": 701,
            "parent_gender": 3381,
            "keywords": [2356, 1041, 2741],
            "meta_keywords": "immunisation, child health, vaccination, immunization",
            "cover_image": {
                "url": "https://bebbopacific.app/sites/somoa/files/styles/content_1200xh_/public/2024-12/information-about-vaccines-cover-image.webp?itok=lpVB7BBh",
                "name": "Information about vaccines cover image.png",
                "alt": "Information about vaccines cover image"
            },
            "related_articles": [],
            "related_video_articles": [],
            "premature": 0,
            "do_not_feature": "0",
            "embedded_images": []
        },
        {
            "id": 246,
            "type": "Article",
            "title": "Teething in babies",
            "created_at": "\u003Ctime datetime=\"2025-05-22T13:06:38+02:00\" class=\"datetime\"\u003EThu, 05/22/2025 - 13:06\u003C/time\u003E\n",
            "updated_at": "\u003Ctime datetime=\"2026-05-19T04:27:59+02:00\" class=\"datetime\"\u003ETue, 05/19/2026 - 04:27\u003C/time\u003E\n",
            "summary": "In most babies, the first teeth appear between 6 and 10 months. The accompanying discomfort experienced by the baby is alleviated by giving him/her cold objects to chew or by gently massaging the gums.",
            "body": "\u003Ch2\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBaby teeth growth\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/h2\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003ETooth germs form in the gums while the baby is still in the womb.  \u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003EIn most children, the first tooth appears at the age of 6 to 10 months, but it can also appear earlier, even at birth, or later, after the first year of life.\u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003EThey appear in a certain order, which is not necessarily always followed.\u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003EUsually, lower central incisors erupt first, followed by upper central and lateral incisors, and by the end of the first year, the child usually has 6 teeth. \u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003EBy the end of the third year, most children have 20 baby teeth.    \u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Ch2\u003ETeeth eruption\u003C/h2\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003EWhile the teeth erupt through the gums, babies are especially sensitive. They need to constantly rub their gums with something, and the place where the teeth erupt is sometimes slightly red and swollen.\u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003ESome children's teeth erupt imperceptibly, but in most children, parents notice certain behavioral changes: they cry or get cranky more, they do not eat normally; they drool, have difficulty falling asleep and wake up more often at night, they chew on everything they can get their hands on: toys, bibs; they ask for a pacifier, get their diapers dirty more often; they rub the ear on the side of the erupting tooth.\u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003EThese changes may be a normal part of development, but are sometimes the result of mild infections.\u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003EIf your child is not well, especially if he/she has a fever or diarrhea, or you are concerned about some other signs of disease, consult a pediatrician.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Ch2\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHelp with teething\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/h2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou will help your baby by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003Egently massaging the gums with a clean finger or brush them with a soft brush;\u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003Eoffering your baby cold items to chew on: a teether or a toy that you kept in the fridge for a while;\u003C/li\u003E\t\u003Cli\u003Epreparing puréed food if you find it necessary.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E",
            "field_type_of_article": 0,
            "category": 386,
            "subcategory": 13851,
            "child_age": [626, 631, 636, 641, 646, 651],
            "child_gender": 701,
            "parent_gender": 3381,
            "keywords": [2976],
            "meta_keywords": "caring for teeth and gums",
            "cover_image": {
                "url": "https://bebbopacific.app/sites/somoa/files/styles/content_1200xh_/public/2025-11/un0203882.webp?itok=IspJkCbN",
                "name": "UN0203882.jpg",
                "alt": "Mother and newborn baby"
            },
            "related_articles": [],
            "related_video_articles": [],
            "premature": 0,
            "do_not_feature": "0",
            "embedded_images": []
        }
